          translation: "Jatayu attained liberation while touching the lotus-hand of Rama, the Lord of the Raghus. Rama performed the funeral rites for Jatayu as if for His own father. That Hari, who is ever compassionate to His devotees, bestowed the supreme destination even upon a bird.",
          commentary: "This verse encapsulates one of the most moving episodes in the Ramayana. Jatayu's moksha through touch of Rama's hand (kara-ambujam) parallels the liberation theology found throughout the Bhagavatam — physical contact with the Lord grants liberation. Rama performing funeral rites 'putravat' (as for a son to a father) is deeply significant: Jatayu was Dasharatha's friend, and Rama honors that bond. The final line — 'pakshino'pi paramam gatim dadau' — that even a bird attained the supreme goal — emphasizes the universal accessibility of divine grace, a key teaching of Bhattathiri. This is echoed in the Gita's declaration that anyone who approaches the Lord with devotion, regardless of birth, attains the highest state.",
