          devanagari: "कुम्भकर्णं रणभूमिमागतं\nदृष्ट्वा सुघोरं वपुषा विभीषणम् ।\nरामबाणैरथ कुम्भकर्णको\nबाहुच्छेदशिरश्छिदा हतः ॥\nभ्रातरं निहतमीक्ष्य रावणो\nदुःखरोषसमाविष्टमानसः ।",
          transliteration: "kumbhakarṇaṁ raṇabhūmimāgataṁ\ndṛṣṭvā sughōraṁ vapuṣā vibhīṣaṇam |\nrāmabāṇairatha kumbhakarṇakō\nbāhucchēdaśiraśchidā hataḥ ||\nbhrātaraṁ nihatamīkṣya rāvaṇō\nduḥkharōṣasamāviṣṭamānasaḥ |",
          translation: "Seeing Kumbhakarna arrive on the battlefield, terrible in form and frightening even to Vibhishana, Rama severed his arms and head with divine arrows, slaying the giant. Witnessing his brother's death, Ravana's mind was seized with grief and rage.",
          commentary: "The slaying of Kumbhakarna is described in Yuddha Kanda chapters 67-69. Rama systematically dismembers the colossus — first the arms, then the head — with precision that demonstrates divine mastery over even the most formidable foe. The mention of Vibhishana's fear is significant: though he has defected to Rama's side, Kumbhakarna was his own brother, creating emotional complexity. Ravana's reaction — 'duhkha-rosha-samavishta-manasah' (mind seized by grief and rage) — marks his psychological descent. Each loss strips away his composure, driving him toward the final, desperate confrontation with Rama himself.",
