          devanagari: "इत्थं बाललीलाभिर्मोहयन् व्रजमण्डलम् |\nपरमात्मा परं ब्रह्म शिशुवेषेण संस्थितः ||\nगुरुवायुपुराधीश तव लीलामृतं पिबन् |\nमरुद्गेहनिवासिंस्त्वं भक्तान् पाहि निरामयम् ||",
          transliteration: "itthaṁ bālalīlābhirmohayan vrajamaṇḍalam |\nparamātmā paraṁ brahma śiśuveṣeṇa saṁsthitaḥ ||\nguruvāyupurādhīśa tava līlāmṛtaṁ piban |\nmarudgehanivāsiṁstvaṁ bhaktān pāhi nirāmayam ||",
          translation: "Thus enchanting the entire circle of Vraja through Your infant pastimes, the Supreme Self, the ultimate Brahman, remained established in the guise of a child. O Lord of Guruvayur, drinking the nectar of Your divine play, O dweller of the temple of the Wind-god, protect Your devotees and grant them freedom from all ailments.",
          commentary: "The concluding verse follows the standard Narayaneeyam pattern of ending each dashaka with a prayer to Guruvayurappan for healing. Bhattathiri summarizes the theological content — the paramātmā appearing as an infant — and then pivots to his personal appeal. The phrase 'nirāmayam' (free from disease) reflects the poem's origin: Bhattathiri composed the Narayaneeyam while suffering from illness, and each dashaka ends with a prayer for cure. This echoes Bhagavatam 10.8.18-19 where Garga describes baby Krishna as equal to Narayana Himself.",
